metadata.name: Mini Lands #56
metadata.description:
Hang around on your own little lands.

W,A,S,D or Arrow keys or use touch controls to move.
Stand near the trees to cut(beat)'em.
Stand near the numbers between the lands to unlock bridges.
Press spacebar or double tap to plant a tree (requires 5 wood).

metadata.name: Chromatic Waves #107
metadata.description:
Threads of color are weaved together, interacting and vibrating.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 3200×2400.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=3200&h=1800 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width and h the desired height. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: Variations #117
metadata.description:
Thousands of rectangles of 8 different colors are positioned on the screen, each color following its own pattern.

By doing so they form shapes that are similar in some aspects, different in others, and together create a larger pattern. Sometimes these shapes are grouped to form another pattern at an intermediate level.

Each iteration, once minted, will also become part of a larger whole that is the generative piece.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 3200×3200.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=5000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: Solid Line #26
metadata.description:
Solid Line is made of square tiles with predefined patterns, disposed randomly, and on top of which is drawn a line. By isolating the colors, this line creates a new structure of seemingly interlaced shapes.

There are three possible level of details, and a rare "Outline" feature that will render only the line layer.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 6000×8000.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=12000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.

metadata.name: saprophyte #229
metadata.description:
saprophyte is a real-time interactive particle system based on the principles of stigmergy. 60,000  particles move around the canvas leaving trails behind them as they move, while each particle decides how to move based on the trails left by other particles around it. You can click to erase the trails in an area, forcing the particles to rebuild their structures anew.

Press "c" to capture an image. By default this will save an image at the resolution of the browser window. If you'd like to save an image at a different resolution, you can press "o" to override the browser's resolution and force the piece to render at a resolution of your choice, and then press "c" to capture the image at your chosen resolution. For best results, wait several seconds after changing the resolution to capture an image, as the piece may need time to adjust to the new resolution.

metadata.name: GEOMORPHISM #183
metadata.description:
A 4444 character magic spell for my rayhatching framework to render thinking rocks.

This piece may take some time to render (about 1-3 minutes, depending on hardware). The rendering time is symbolic of the vastness and agelessness of these rock structures, it is recommended to use the rendering time to contemplate deeply the concept of time spans so incredibly long, that to experience them they would have to overwrite your memories several times and thus are impossible to truly comprehend.

To ponder how, if they are so old, how come some of them float? Are these rocks the fixtures and has time and space itself eroded around them?

This project uses an approach called "rejection sampling". This means the program generates a random set of parameters, and then checks/previews how the resulting image would look. It measures the amount of visible objects, light and shadows, and then determines whether these fall into acceptable ranges. If not, it generates a new set of parameters. For certain hashes over a 100 parameter sets may be checked before it accepts the image.

The features of this project are "cliff", "ground", "thing" and "sky". These are not parameters, they are actual measurements of the resulting image, indicating what percentage of the view is occupied.

This piece can be saved as an SVG and plotted. It is recommended to run a path order optimization tool such as vpype or axicli, this will greatly reduce plotting time.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&w=.25 : The line width in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.

The line width is set to 0.25 millimetres to suit most common fine liner pen stroke widths when plotting. 

If you don't intend to plot this piece, perhaps also try rendering it at 0.2 or even 0.1 millimetres line width, for an even more detailed image (it will also take longer to render).

(c) 2022 by Piter Pasma

metadata.name: White Mountain Winter #100
metadata.description:
White Mountain Winter is collaboration between myself and the machine to describe scenes that are real, or were. Yet perhaps now foreign, or out of time, or far away. I provide the seed of a dream I remember, and trust the machine to help make it real again.

I grew up in a town much like some of these, homes dispersed throughout the valley beneath the shadows of the mountains rising around. This is a tribute to the memory of wintertime in that place; bleak, cold, grey, with the light seemingly always fading. Yet at the same time, the feeling of calm, solace, peace resonating through. Exposed to the mountain elements, yet protected by them. A delicate arrangement, but essential.

The seed of magic I remember is present in the experience of falling snow at dusk. Large flakes tumbling down and blanketing everything, no end in sight. The most striking thing is the silence. The fallen snow absorbing all distraction, insisting that your focus be sharpened to a singularity; right there, right then.

---
- Best rendered in Chrome browser (best performance, & canvas blur - please be patient :)
- Made with p5js
- Press "s" to save png

metadata.name: ProtoCephalopod:01 #14
metadata.description:
ProtoCephalopod:01 is the first Cephalopod in my expanded 3D Protobytes series, begun in 2004.

Protobytes is an investigation into generative, artificial lifeforms, created algorithmically through code and math. The original 2004 series (http://www.iragreenberg.com/ira_greenberg_data/code/protobytes/) were built of overlapping 2D forms using ActionScript. ProtoCephalopods are generative 3D models built with WebGL (three.js), TypeScript and my own PByte.js library.

An additional limited 1/1 series of ProtoCephalopods, finished with Stable Diffusion, may be viewed on Mint Gold Dust https://www.mintgolddust.com/artists/ira-greenberg

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> came
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
p: screen capture


Note:
Please post your favorite screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: CRAYONS #191
metadata.description:
Sometimes we like the feeling of being citizens of the places we visit. Our senses adapt to capture in detail the signs of the environment. It is then when we begin to breathe the color that surrounds us and places us in that unique setting.

This is how this inspired collection is born and grows, the colors that enchant us as children on a sheet of paper and now serve to paint every place we visit.

The 6 color palettes of this collection aim to transport us to all those places.

Paris: Its pastel tones strolling along the Trocadero on the banks of the Seine.

Berlin: How to tell the story with color in the graffiti of the East Side Gallery and the wall.

Mexico: Its flavor is in the rainbow of its embroideries, alebrijes and altars.

Kenya: Sunrises and sunsets that impregnate the retina with the tones of the savannah.

Costa Rica: Pure life, pure green, from gentle to intense Monte Lluvioso.

Colombia: Seas of flowers flood the streets with colors and aromas celebrating the Feria De Las Flores

High-resolution png downloads are available by pressing number keys 1 (3000px), 2 (6000px), or 3 (9000px).

metadata.name: FX(T)RASH #86
metadata.description:
Imagine having Van Gogh's ear in a little box, getting your grubby hands on Banksy's stencils or Zancan's plotter! Well, here's something just as awesome - This is your chance to collect some trash straight from the King of Trash Art himself, Robness!

---

NOR44 & ROBNESS V2 JOIN FORCES TO CREATE A SPECIAL GENERATIVE PROJECT IN HONOR OF THE SECOND #TEZTRASH EVENT ON 12/21/22.  TEZTRASH IS A TEZOS COMMUNITY DAY WHEN THE CRYPTONATIVE ART MOVEMENT #TRASHART AND TRASH ART IN GENERAL IS CELEBRATED.  THE PREVIOUS TEZTRASH EVENT WAS A MONUMENTAL HIT ON TWITTER AND THIS TIME AROUND WE'VE DECIDED TO CONCOCT AN EPIC GENERATIVE DROP WHILST KEEPING THE TRASH ART ETHOS EMBEDDED IN THE WORK. HERE WE PLAY WITH THE NOTION OF 'TRASHING JPEGS' AND REINSERTING A PHYSICAL YET GENERATIVE REPRESENTATION OF THAT IDEA. ENJOY AND HAPPY TEZTRASH 2.0 DAY!

---

This generative artwork is composed of many layers of pre-rendered images with code utilized to stylize as well as randomly position, rotate and scale these elements, creating potentially infinite unique compositions resembling real-world outputs from a Photocopier/Copy Machine that's seen better days.
